t-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Both people of shorter and taller stature can find it difficult to find the ideal exercise bike. Most machines are built standardized to fit the widest range of users, so if you stand out in any way you may have to research well before making a purchase. Generally, the best spin bike for short people will not work as well for someone taller.</p><p>For example, an exercise bike for petite people will have a lower seat height range and fewer settings. The handlebars may be positioned lower to be easier to reach if they’re not adjustable by height already. The frame of the bike and the seat may be smaller in comparison as well. The frame dimensions and type will also play a role in accessibility, with more compact frames with step-through designs being more common on exercise bikes for small people. Here’s a quick table breakdown of some of the main differences:</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Liquid" data-key="liquid" data-atomgroup="module" id="m-1697283647471" class="module-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-liquid" data-ver="1.1" data-id="1697283647471" data-name="Right click on this, and choose Edit Code."><div class="module gf_module- gf_module--lg gf_module--md gf_module--sm gf_module--xs {{extraClass}}"><div class="rte__table-wrapper"><table dir="ltr" style="table-layout: fixed; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial; width: 0px; border-collapse: collapse; border: none;" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><colgroup><col width="194"><col width="320"><col width="300"></colgroup><tbody><tr style="height: 21px;"><td style="border-width: 1px; border-style: solid; border-color: #b7b7b7 #b7b7b7 #b7b7b7 #cccccc; border-image: initial; overflow: hidden; padding: 2px 3px; vertical-align: middle; background-color: #ff990